e, the volume traces two parallel trends in the evolution of the field—first, comedy’s development into myriad subgenres, formats, and discourses, a tendency that has led many popular commentators to characterize the present as a “comedy zeitgeist”; and second, comedy studies’ new focus on the ways in which comedy increasingly circulates in “serious” discursive realms, including politics, economics, race, gender, and cultural power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aComedy filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aComedy filmszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aComedyxHistoryy20th century. 0aComedyxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aComedyxSocial aspects. 0aMotion picturesy20th century. 0aMotion pictureszUnited Statesy20th century. 0aPopular culturexHistoryy20th century. 0aPopular culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aTelevision comediesxHistory and criticism. 0aTelevision comedieszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film / Genres / Comedy.2bisacsh1 aMarx, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarx, Nick, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSienkiewicz, Matt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSienkiewicz, Matt, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31599640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477316016423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477316016/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK